{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17538969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17538969"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:35:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16423"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16423"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.57,0.07,0.04,0.15,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9114"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65161"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9114","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9114"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16423"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50598"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"1343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"5320"},{"type":"tags","id":"11059"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21652"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33784"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43634"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65161"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 48-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of severe hot flushes and night sweats affecting her sleep and quality of life. She completed treatment for breast cancer eight months ago, which included mastectomy and chemotherapy. The cancer was oestrogen and progesterone receptor positive. She takes tamoxifen and has no other medical conditions. She does not smoke and drinks minimal alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management for her menopausal symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Venlafaxine","Oestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy","Black cohosh","Tibolone","Combined oestrogen and progesterone hormone replacement therapy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with menopausal symptoms following chemotherapy for hormone receptor-positive breast cancer. The management of these symptoms requires careful consideration of the risk of cancer recurrence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined oestrogen and progesterone hormone replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in patients with hormone receptor-positive breast cancer as it significantly increases the risk of cancer recurrence. The presence of both oestrogen and progesterone receptors on the original tumour means that exposure to either hormone could stimulate cancer cell growth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOestrogen-only hormone replacement therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is also contraindicated for the same reason. Even without progesterone, oestrogen alone could stimulate cancer recurrence in hormone receptor-positive disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETibolone\u003C/strong\u003E is a synthetic steroid with oestrogenic, progestogenic, and androgenic effects. It is contraindicated in breast cancer survivors due to its hormonal effects and potential to increase recurrence risk.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVenlafaxine\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice. As a selective serotonin and noradrenaline reuptake inhibitor, it effectively manages vasomotor symptoms without hormonal effects. It has been shown to reduce the frequency and severity of hot flushes in breast cancer survivors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlack cohosh\u003C/strong\u003E is a herbal remedy sometimes used for menopausal symptoms. However, its safety in breast cancer survivors is uncertain, and there are concerns about its possible oestrogenic effects. Additionally, its efficacy is not well established in clinical trials.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther non-hormonal options for managing menopausal symptoms in breast cancer survivors include lifestyle modifications (avoiding triggers, maintaining cool environment), other selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors like paroxetine (noting potential interactions with tamoxifen), and gabapentin.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hormone replacement therapy is contraindicated in patients with hormone receptor-positive breast cancer due to increased risk of recurrence.","Non-hormonal options are the mainstay of managing menopausal symptoms in breast cancer survivors.","Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors can effectively manage vasomotor symptoms in breast cancer survivors."],"references":["Australasian Menopause Society. Breast cancer and menopause [Internet]. East Melbourne: Australasian Menopause Society; c2023 [cited 2024 Nov 25]. Available from: https://www.menopause.org.au/hp/information-sheets/breast-cancer-and-menopause?highlight=WyJicmVhc3QiLCJjYW5jZXIiXQ=="]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50598"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16423"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50598","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50598"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T18:04:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T18:05:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9114"}},"content":{"data":{